@NODE Introduction

@{B}Introduction@{UB}

  This is a program launcher, window manager, and Virtual Screen manager.

  +----------------------------------------------------+
  | +----+ +--------+ +--------+ +--------+            |
  | |OnGo| |Screen 1| |Screen 2| |Screen 3|            |
  | +----+ +--------+ +--------+ +--------+            |
  +----------------------------------------------------+

  Programs can be launched via Workbench's TOOL menu, or via the
"OnGo" button.  When clicked on, a configurable popup menu appears,
with as many tools and sub-menus as you like (up to a limit of 65535
items PER menu!)

  Alternatively, select some icons from the workbench, and select
one of the new (configurable) items from the TOOLs menu.

  The three other buttons control which virtual screen is visible.
I had considered making it a TaskBar, á lŕ Windows '95, but having
used Windows '95, and noted that the TaskBar controls @{i}windows@{ui}
and not @{i}tasks@{ui}, and felt that the ones other people had written
for the Amiga were a bit sluggish, I decided against this.  I didnt
really like the AutoScroll under Workbench, and felt that the other
XWindows Virtual Window managers for the Amiga were a bit buggy,
so I wrote my own.

  You can also iconify windows on the workbench screen to a
button on the OnGo bar.  Click on them to uniconify.

  The tools can be launched with a workbench sytle environment,
or a cli environment.


@ENDNODE

@NODE Features

@{B}Features@{UB}

  ° Is a commodity
  ° Removeable
  ° Low profile (preserves valuable screen space)
  ° Relatively small (compared to others I have seen)
  ° Launches programs with either workbench or cli environments
  ° Configurable look (3DLOOK, NEWLOOK or XLOOK)
  ° Virtual Screens!
  ° Window iconification
  ° Shortens workbench to avoid concealing icons
  ° Adds items to TOOL menu (cf EasyTM)
  ° Graphics
  ° Dynamic menus, sorted
  ° AutoHide
  ° Draggable bar

  See @{" History " link History} for more details.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Requirements

@{B}System Requirements@{UB}

  OnGo v2.6.1 requires the WBStart.Library 2.0, or the WBStart-Handler,
both written by Stefan Becker.  The library is available from aminet.

  If you have the datatypes library, you will also have graphics.

  OnGo was developed on a KS3.1 A1200(AT).  I have had it working on
a KS3.1 A2000 (MC68000).  It is supposed to work on KS2.0 machines
too, but I do not have access to one, so I can not test this.  If
you get it running on any other kickstart, please let @{"me" link author} know.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Installation

@{B}Installation@{UB}

  Automagically : double click on the installer script.

  Manually :
	° Drag OnGo to your WBStartUp drawer
	° Drag OnGo.Config to your ENVARC: drawer
	° Drag OnGo.Config to your ENV: drawer
	° (Optionally) Put the documentation somewhere sensible.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Usage

@{B}Usage@{UB}

  (ps - sorry if this sounds patronizing - I'm drunk 8*O )

  To use the @{b}OnGo@{ub} button with the mouse :-
    Click on the button with the left mouse button, and hold down.
    A menus will appear.
    Menu items with submenus are denoted by a '»' mark.  Moving
      over them will cause the submenu to appear.
    When your chosen tool is highlighted, let go of the left mouse button.


  To use the @{b}OnGo@{ub} button with the keyboard :-
    Activate the bar by clicking in it.
    Press the space bar.  The menu will appear.
    Use the up and down cursor keys to navigate the menus.  Using
      shift will jump to the top/bottom of the menu.
    Use the right cursor key or the space bar, or the return key to
      select, or enter a submenu.
    Use the ESCAPE button, or the left cursor key to close the current
      menu and go back up one, or end the selection altogether.


  To change virtual screens :
    Click on the unselected button corresponding to the screen to
      switch to;
    OR press 1,2 or 3 to switch to that screen,
    OR press the hotkey combination (by default, LALT and F1, F2 or F3)


  To iconify a window on the workbench :
    Activate the window.
    Press the Iconify Hot Key (by default :RAmiga \\)


  To uniconify an iconified window :
    Click on the button representing the window.


  Pressing the hotkey combination (by default : CTRL LALT O) does the
  same as showing/hiding the interface via the Exchange application.
  Note : Hiding the interface closes all virtual screens (i.e. all
  hidden windows appear).


  Sending the program a CTRL-C, will remove the program.


  To use items from the TOOLS menu :-
    If you dont already know, you should not be using this program!


@ENDNODE

@NODE Configuration

@{B}Configuration@{UB}

  Alas, the prefs program is still under developement (it has
gone from a few drawings on the back of a used envelope, to a
program that opens a window).

  So until it sprouts and grows into a big healthy program,
you will have to do everything manually.  Do not use TABS.


@{B}OnGo Bar@{UB}

The main program is set up through icon tooltypes.

CX_HOTKEY
This defines the key combination that will hide or show OnGo Bar.
e.g. "CX_HOTKEY=CTRL LALT o"

CX_PRIORITY
This defines the priority of OnGo in the commodities chain.  You
can change it from -128 to +127, but the only difference it will
make is when the CX_HOTKEY is checked for.
e.g. "CX_PRIORITY=0"

CX_SHOW
This determines whether the OnGo bar appears when you first load the
program.  OnGo is hardly worth using with this value set to "NO".
e.g. "CX_SHOW=YES"

TOOLSFILE
This tells OnGo where to look for the menu configuration file.
By default, this is set to ENV:OnGo.Config.  If you store your
config file somewhere else, change this setting to tell Ongo
where to find it.
e.g. "TOOLSFILE=ENV:OnGo.Config"

TOOLSARC
This was meant for the prefs program.  Currently does NOTHING.
e.g. "TOOLSARC=ENVARC:OnGo.Config"

PREFSPRG
This setting tells the OnGo main program where to find the
preferences program.
e.g. "PREFSPRG=SYS:Prefs/OnGo-Prefs"

POSITION
This determines whether the OnGo Bar appears at the top or at the
bottom of the screen.  There are two possible values: TOP and BOTTOM.
e.g. "POSITION=TOP"

SHORTBENCH
This option will shrink the Workbench backdrop window to prevent
the OnGo Bar from obscuring icons on the workbench backdrop.
It's possible values are TRUE or FALSE
e.g. "SHORTBENCH=TRUE"

GADGETTEXT
This determines the label on the OnGo "Start Button"
e.g. "GADGETTEXT= OnGo "

NUMVSCREENS
This allows you to set the number of virtual screens.  The default
and minimum is 3.  The maximum number is 9.

SCREENTEXT1, SCREENTEXT2, SCREENTEXT3...
These options determine the labels on the three virtual screen buttons.
e.g. "SCREENTEXT1=Screen 1"

SCREENKEY1, SCREENKEY2, SCREENKEY3...
These options determine the hot key combinations that will
switch to each virtual screen.
e.g. "SCREENKEY1 =lalt f1"

ICONKEY
This determines the hot key combination that will iconify the
current active window on the workbench screen.  You could specify
a mouse based "hot key", but remember that it iconifies the ACTIVE
window.  You cannot iconify backdrop windows, or the OnGo bar.  You
can make other windows non-iconifyable with the "STICKY" option below.
e.g. "ICONKEY=rcommand \"
e.g. "ICONKEY=rawmouse leftbutton rbutton mouse_rightpress"

LOOK
This allows you to change the style of popup menus.  There are
currently three styles.  A 3DLOOK, or a style guide compliant
NEWLOOK, or a unix like XLOOK.
e.g. "LOOK=3DLOOK"

MINWIDTH
This sets the minimum width of a menu.  Menus are normally created
just big enough to hold the graphics, the sub-menu mark, and the
items' text.  This setting will enlarge small menus to this minimum.
e.g. "MINWIDTH=0"

MENULAP
This determines how much of a menu is left uncovered my a sub menu.
The vakue is in percent.  Try values such as 0, 50, 75 and 100 to
get a better idea of how it works.
e.g. "MENULAP=75"

MENUDELAY
This sets a delay, in tenths of a second, before a sub-menu is opened.
This can be helpful when moving the mouse from one end of the menu to
the other, by preventing OnGo from opening every menu in between.
e.g. "MENUDELAY=5"

DRAG
This is a temporary hack to enable the user to drag the bar vertically.
The initial position is currently determined by the POSITION tooltype.
In a future version, this will be superceeded by a "FLOAT" option for
POSITION tooltype, and an XPOS and YPOS tooltypes.
Current values are TRUE and FALSE.  Setting DRAG to true will disable
the SHORTBENCH patch.
e.g. "DRAG=TRUE"

AUTOHIDE
This will cause the OnGo bar to appear when the user moves the mouse
over it, and shrink at other times.  Setting this option will
disable both DRAG and SHORTBENCH options.
Current values are TRUE and FALSE.
e.g. "AUTOHIDE=TRUE"


The program can be terminated in three ways.
    ° Send it a REMOVE message through Exchange
    ° Send it a CTRL-C
    ° Use a QUIT menu item.


@{B}OnGo Config file@{UB}

The OnGo.Config file contains types of settings.
    ° Names of tasks whose windows must not be iconified or
      switched to a virtual screen.
    ° Items for workbench's TOOLS menu
    ° Items for the popup menus

The current version is text based.  Change it using your favourite
text editor.  Each line corresponds to one "item".  You may leave
blank lines, and include comments at the end of a line by preceding
it with a ";"



Non-iconifiable windows are set up with the following command.

    STICKY "<task>"

You may have as many, or as few of these as you like.



Items to go under workbench's TOOLS menu are specified as follows:-

  APPM "<item name>" "<program to run>" "<path of program>" <LaunchMethod> <StackSize> <Priority>

The LaunchMethod should be :-

		      |  Workbench  |  Cli
  --------------------+-------------+-------
  No args             |     16      |  32
  Once with each arg  |     17      |  33
  Once with all args  |     18      |  34 @{"*" link Bugs 6}

The stack should be at least 4096.  None of the items may be ommitted,
although you may specify "" if you wish.



Items under the popup menu can be set up similarly:-

  ITEM "<item name>" "<program to run>" "<path of program>" <LaunchMethod> <StackSize> <Priority>

However, the only valid launch methods are 16 or 32 (as above).
None of the items may be ommitted.

You may create sub-menus with the "MENU <menu name>" command, and
terminate them with "MENU END" :-

  MENU "<sub-menu-name>"
  MENU END

Additionally, there are a number of "special" item commands:-

  QUIT  "<item name>"
  HIDE  "<item name>"
  RELOAD "<item name>"
  LABEL "<item name>"
  DISK  "<item name>" "<directory>"

"QUIT" will cause OnGo to terminate.  "HIDE" will hide the OnGo bar.
There is no matching "SHOW".  "RELOAD" will cause OnGo to reload the
config file, but not re-read the icon's tooltypes.  "LABEL" will
create a menu item that cannot be selected.  "DISK" will create a
special sub-menu that gets its item from a directory on disk.


Finally, you may also specify a graphic to use with ITEM, MENU, QUIT,
HIDE, RELOAD, LABEL and DISK.  This option should be the last one on
the relevant line, but before the comment.
e.g.  DISK "Commodities" "SYS:Tools/Commodities" ICON="S:OnGoIcons/Drawer.br"


@ENDNODE

@NODE Bugs

@{B}Bugs@{UB}

  OnGo:
	° Not very much error reporting. (i.e. none)
	° LaunchMethod CLI-ALL can generate a command line longer
	    than AmigaDOS can normally handle.  You should use
	    CLI-EACH instead.
	° Somethimes window depth gadgets seem to stop working,
	    when useing the virtual screens.  hmmm.
	° When a window is redisplayed, it isnt always refreshed properly.
	° Iconification and Virtual screens does not seem to work
	    with all programs.  @{" Click here " link BadWin}
	° Can crash somethimes when you reload or close down OnGo.
	    It definitely crashes if you have a missing menu file.


  OnGo-Prefs:
	° Does nothing (yet).  Oh, the supplied file named
	    OnGo-Prefs was a little joke, aimed at the people
	    who keep telling me to write "stub" code.


  I have a KS3.1 A1200 (AT) 28Mhz '030 with MMU, FPU and SCSI;
and an old CM8833-II, running at 640x256 (PAL).

  I have been told OnGo works on A4000s, but not on A500+.  Please
mail @{"me" link author} if you get it working on any other machines.

@ENDNODE


@NODE BadWin "Programs who do not like being iconified"

@{B}Programs who do not like being iconified@{UB}

Help me to help you avoid crashes with the window iconification, by
reporting any programs who do not like having their windows iconified.

So far,

    ° Ordering
    ° Tool manager
    ° Biorhythms


You can instruct OnGo to avoid these programs with the STICKY command
in the menu file.  @{" Configuration " link configuration}

@ENDNODE


@NODE Future

@{B}Future@{UB}


  Yeah, I know, I've hardly done any of this.  I've been busy.


  OnGo really needs a preferences editor, followed by some nice
graphics, and fixing that @{i}irritating@{ui} bug that leaves grey bits
around the graphics.  I'd also like to write a MagicMenus/SiliconMenus
type program too.


  Other than that, here are the _other_ things I have in mind :-

	° Fix @{" bugs " link Bugs}
	° Position LEFT, RIGHT, and FLOAT
	° Track window activation, and pop them to the front.
	° Better error reporting, such as IF and WHY something failed.
	° Add more features to the install script for EXPERTS
	° More graphics which change; and use icons' images
	° User-definable OnGo gadget imagery
	° Dynamic menus (via "Promises")
	    ° Screens and windows
	    ° Tasks
	    ° Commodities
	° A button to add more virtual screens on-the-fly
	° Sticky windows list, by window title.
	° Better icons (I'm not much of an artist).  I'm looking for
	  MagicWorkbench, NewIcons, and some IconPack style ones.
	  I'd like them to have an "active" or "on-the-ball" feel.

	° Workbench argument passing, with an AppWindow
	° Digital clock and stopwatch (a la mac)
	    - unlikely.  I'm happy with Yak
	° REXX environment
	° Requesters for CLI and REXX environments
	    - Unlikely.  Use `Requestfile` or `RequestChoice` in a script
	° AppIcons
	    - Unlikely.  I dont use them.  If you want them, mail me.
	° Normal Intuition Menus
	    - What would you want here?
	° Keyboard Shortcuts
	° Enable/disable items
	° Multiple Columns
	° Option to keep OnGo window foremost
	    - sugguest how to implement this _efficiently_
	° Screen Jumping
	    - Unlikely.  It was always meant for WB
	° Rip-off windows (XWindows style!)
	° Option to make menus appear on a MIDDLE MOUSE BUTTON!
	    - Not until I get a 3 button mouse
	° Resizeable OnGo bar (a la windows 95)
	° Hotkey for VirtualScreen Cycling
	    - Easy to do, but I dont consider it necessary when I
	    only have 3 virtual screens.  Mail me if you want it.
	° A single line command line, with filename completion and history
	° (Intuition) Screen iconification
	° Allow "renting" out space to other programs, so you could
	    write code to add a button to the OnGoBar.
	° I might compile 020, 030 and 040 versions if I get
	    sufficient requests.  Alternatively, download the source
	    from aminet:util/cdity.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "YourHelp" "I need your help"

@{B}Your help@{UB}

If I have to do everything myself, it will take a very long time.
Every one can help by:-

    ° Reporting any bugs.
    ° Telling me what hardware/software configurations
       it works OK on (helps me to track bugs)
    ° Telling me which features you use.
    ° Telling me what features you would like included.
    ° Sugguest a reasonable maximum number of iconified windows.
	Current limit is 16.  Do not say "no limit", but I might
	allow it to be set by a tooltype.
    ° Tell me which programs do not like being iconified. @{" Click " link Badwin}


Artists can be of particular help by :-

    ° Sending me icons for the main program and documentation.
	I'd like some MagicWorkBench, NewIcon and IconPack
	style icons
    ° Mini graphics for menu items.  Remember that these must
	have TWO pictures next to each other.  The left one is
	"normal", and the right one is "selected".


Programmers can help by :-

    ° I'm having trouble getting rid of that grey stuff around
	graphics.  This is most noticible when an item is hilighted,
	or if you have set the style to NEWLOOK.  I've tried flood
	filling around it, but that sometimes fails.
    ° I'm considering changing the pen used for active text in
	3DLOOK and XLOOK modes.  Currently I use TEXT pen, but
	I think IMPORTANT TEXT, or ACTIVE WINDOW TITLE might be
	a better choice.  What do you think?


@ENDNODE

@NODE History

@{B}History@{UB}

2.6.1   11th November 1996 [minor update]
	° OnGo did not run without datatypes library, which is not
	present on KS2 machines.  I traced the problem to having
	forgot to suppress the auto-open library feature, by declaring
	the library base as initialised to NULL.  Hopefully, it WILL
	now work on KS machines.


2.6     5th November 1996
	° Fixed a bug where a selected, but unopened submenu would
	    appear when the OnGo button was next activated.  Thanks
	    to Michal Rybarski for letting me know.
	° Fixed a refresh bug to do with AutoHide.
	° Read routine now accepts TABS (requested by Stefan Zivkovic)
	° Fixed AllocVecs and RdArgs calls.  Thanks to Bert for this.
	° Added code to use WBStart-Handler


2.5     28th August 1996 [minor update]
	° Added AUTOHIDE option
	° Added DRAG option
	° Fixed (hopefully!) read routine, so it now runs on more
	    machines.  Thanks to Ray Price for sorting it out.


2.4     20th August 1996 [minor update]
	° Fixed MENUDELAY bug.  The ticks really are TENTHS of a
	    second now!
	° Added a special DISK name, "#?:" which produces a list
	    of all mounted volumes.
	° Added a tooltype NUMVSCREENS so you can set the number
	   of virtual screens.


2.3     11th August 1996 [minor update]
	° Fixed a bug where using keys on disk based menus would
	    always launch the LAST program in the list, regardless
	    of what was actually selected.
	° Fixed a number of bugs with the DISK type, where directories
	    with zero or one item tended to mess things up.  Thanks
	    to Stanislav Kneifl for drawing this to my attention.
	° Plugged a serious memory leak from the DISK type.


2.2     29th July 1996 [minor update]
	° Quashed a *stupid* bug which caused a crash if you returned
	    to a screen from which you had iconified a window.
	    Thanks to Saalek for reporting this.
	° Improved the package (docs, installer etc...) a bit.


2.1     24th July 1996
	° Modified promises to sort alphabetically, using a
	    super fast merge sort routine.
	° Fixed a (harmless) bug which allowed you to ICONIFY
	    windows, or "switch virtual screens" when the
	    OnGoBar was closed.
	° Fixed a couple of bugs with XLOOK - WHY didnt anyone
	    tell me it was broken???  Does no one use it?
	° Added basic graphics


2.0     20th July 1996
	° Added "Promises", allowing dynamic menus.
	° Added a DISK item type
	° Added a STICKY item type


1.5.2   18th July 1996
	° Added a LABEL type
	° Added a half second delay before displaying menus, to
	    avoid opening menus you're just passing over.
	° Some clean up of code


1.5     14th July 1996
	° Fixed key to activate the OnGo button (oops!)
	° Added Window Iconification hot key


1.4     7th July 1996
	° Fixed SHORTBENCH to work OK with FULLBENCH type programs
	° Added POSITION tooltype, to have OnGo window at top or
	    bottom of screen.
	° Fixed bug where window opens on default public screen


1.3     22nd June 1996
	° Added hotkeys for virtual screen switching
	° Added XLOOK
	° Fixed refresh bug
	° Set MEMF_REVERSE and MEMF_PUBLIC on all AllocVec()'s


1.2     19th June 1996
	° Added SHORTBENCH tooltype option and code
	° Added VIRTUAL SCREENS!
	° Created ToggleButtonClass (under 1.5K!)
	° Added auto sizing buttons (for Virtual Screens)
	° Added approriate tooltypes for vscreens
	° Removed LEFT, TOP, WIDTH, BORDERTYPE tooltypes (obsolete)
	° Improved Keyboard usage
	° Fixed menus to hang left when right up against rightmost edge
	° Reordered Config reading code to make it (slightly) faster
	° Added a teeny bit more to the docs


1.1     16th June 1996
	° Fixed Reloading of menus (crashed before - oops!)
	° Fixed DRI pens
	° Fixed right gutter ( » )
	° Protection code against too mane MENU END's
	° Added HIDE and RELOAD types
	° Added APPMENU code from EasyTM, and a new type APPM


1.0     14th June 1996
	° Added Launch code from EasyTM
	° Fixed position of initial menu to above the gadget
	° Added size/window position settings
	° Added auto-sensing size/window
	° Added gadget text, and submenu character options
	° Added border settings
	° Added some icons
	° Added menu overlap control
	° Added minimum width
	° Recompiled (now SMALLER!)


0.9     6th June 1996
